Certainly! Below is a simple C++ program that achieves this. The program reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word provided by the user. It uses the `<fstream>` library for file operations and `<iostream>` for console input/output.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

// Function to count occurrences of a word in a given line
int countOccurrences(const std::string& line, const std::string& word) {
    int count = 0;
    std::string temp;
    std::istringstream iss(line);

    // Read each word in the line
    while (iss >> temp) {
        // Increment count if the word is found
        if (temp == word) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    return count;
}

int main() {
    std::string filename;
    std::string word;
    std::string line;
    int totalCount = 0;

    // Get the filename and word to search from the user
    std::cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    std::cin >> filename;

    std::cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
    std::cin >> word;

    // Open the file
    std::ifstream file(filename);

    // Check if the file was opened successfully
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Could not open the file - '" << filename << "'" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Read the file line by line
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        // Count the occurrences of the word in the current line
        totalCount += countOccurrences(line, word);
    }

    // Close the file
    file.close();

    // Output the result
    std::cout << "The word '" << word << "' occurred " << totalCount << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To compile and run this program, save it as `word_count.cpp`, and on the command line, execute the following commands:

```bash
g++ -o word_count word_count.cpp
./word_count
```

When the program runs, it will ask for the filename and the word to search for. Make sure the text file you want to read is in the same directory as the executable, or provide an absolute path to the file.

Note: This program does a simple string comparison and will count words that exactly match the input. It does not account for punctuation or case sensitivity. If you need a more robust solution that can handle these cases, you'll need to implement additional logic for word normalization and comparison.
